references: To explore why nnUNet can outperform other models on cases of A,C,D to B and A,B,C to D, we train nnUNet models with 100% labeled data only from domain B or domain D. Then we test the models with data from domain A, B, C and D. As shown in Table A7, the model trained on domain B can achieve 85.81% Dice on domain D (highest Dice compared to A and C). Also, the model trained on domain D can achieve 84.35% Dice on domain B (highest Dice compared to A and C). Hence, nnUNet possibly overfits the source domains e.g. B, to achieve the best performance on domains (e.g. D) similar to B. However, other methods have to generalise to distinct domains i.e. A and C, which causes slightly worse performance on the domains similar to source domains.
